{{Infobox football league season |competition=Mongolia National Championship |season=2001 |winners= [[Khangarid]] |continentalcup1= |continentalcup1 qualifiers= |relegated= |league topscorer= |biggest away win= |biggest home win= |highest scoring= |matches= |total goals= |longest wins= |longest unbeaten= |longest winless= |longest losses= |highest attendance= |lowest attendance= |average attendance= |prevseason=[[2000 Mongolia Premier League|2000]] |nextseason=[[2002 Mongolia Premier League|2002]] }}
The '''2001 Mongolian National Championship''' was the thirty-fourth recorded edition of top flight [[Association football|football]] in [[Mongolia]] and the sixth season of the [[Mongolian Premier League]], which took over as the highest level of competition in the country from the previous Mongolian National Championship.<ref name="RSSSF1">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mongchamp.html |title=Mongolia&nbsp;– List of Champions |last1=Morrison |first1=Neil |last2=Zlotkowski |first2=Andre |last3=Kubusch |first3=Lars |last4=Batmunkh |first4=Jargalsaikhan |date=8 October 2015 |website=www.rsssf.com |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=22 December 2015}}</ref> [[Khangarid]] from [[Erdenet]] were champions, their first title and the first time the new league had been won by a team from outside [[Ulaanbaatar]], [[Mon-Uran]] were runners up, with [[Sonor (football club)|Sonor]] in third place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mong01.html |title=Mongolia 1901 |last1=Schöggl |first1=Hans |date=22 June 2004 |website=rsssf.com/ |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref>
